<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/F7E13617-2678-475B-99E4-31479C92038D"><gtr:id>F7E13617-2678-475B-99E4-31479C92038D</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Aberdeen</gtr:name><gtr:department>Computing Science</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Office</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Regent Walk</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Aberdeen</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Aberdeenshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>AB24 3FX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/F7E13617-2678-475B-99E4-31479C92038D"><gtr:id>F7E13617-2678-475B-99E4-31479C92038D</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Aberdeen</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Office</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Regent Walk</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Aberdeen</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Aberdeenshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>AB24 3FX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/5467922C-2BCD-4E7B-8B10-6CB58F1D9C9D"><gtr:id>5467922C-2BCD-4E7B-8B10-6CB58F1D9C9D</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Advaith</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Siddharthan</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/6755B81E-636A-4DCF-B0A8-87A2C34BA7B4"><gtr:id>6755B81E-636A-4DCF-B0A8-87A2C34BA7B4</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Napoleon</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Katsos</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-000-22-3272-A"><gtr:id>8D580109-DDA9-42EC-B10F-0D8DCFA77BF7</gtr:id><gtr:title>Studying the appropriateness of different formulations of a discourse relation in context</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-000-22-3272-A</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>There are many reasons why a writer would want to choose one formulation of a discourse relation over another. For example consider the case of causality:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Fructose-induced hypertension occurs because salt absorption by the intestine and kidney increases.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Increased salt absorption by the intestine and kidney causes fructose-induced hypertension. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>These are two of many possible formulations that convey the same information. Human writers prefer different formulations in different contexts, but not much is know about what governs their decisions. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project will create a corpus of examples of reformulation from real scientific texts.&amp;nbsp; These will be annotated with human judgment for grammaticality and coherence and then used to train a computer (natural language generator) to rank the felicity of different reformulations.&amp;nbsp; In addition, this project will investigate whether readers with and without expertise in the scientific discipline find it easier to understand certain formulations than others.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project is a novel collaboration between a computational linguist and an experimental linguist that directly applies experimental results to computational tasks. This is the first step towards building applications that can reformulate technical writing for different audiences in a principled manner.&lt;/p>

